everybody 's talking today about happiness .
i have some people count the number of books that have been published with " happiness " in the title in the last five years , and they called after about 40 on , and there were a lot more .
there is a huge wave of interest in happiness among researchers .
there 's a lot of coaching .
everybody would like to make people happier .
but despite all this flood of work , there are several cognitive traps that make it almost impossible to think clearly about happiness .
and my talk today will be mainly from these cognitive traps .
this is for amateurs who think about their own happiness , and it is important for scientists who think about happiness , because it turns out that we are just as confused as everyone else .
the first of these traps is a reluctance to admit complexity .
it turns out that the word is happiness simply no longer useful word , because we apply it on too many different things .
i think there is a particular meaning , which we could confine , but by and large , this is something that we have to give up , and we 're going to have to accept the complicated way of looking at it , what 's wellbeing .
the second case is a confusion between experience and memory : basically it is between happy in his life and be happy about his life or happy with his life .
and these are two very different concepts , and they 're both lumped together in the vision of happiness .
and the third is the illusion of concentration , and this is the unfortunate fact that we can think about a factor that influenced by the wellbeing , without distorting its importance .
i mean , this is a real cognitive trap .
there is simply no way to get it right .
now , i would like to start with an example of someone who had a question and answer session after one of my lectures , who wrote a story . [ unclear ... ] he said he heard a symphony , and it was absolutely wonderful music , and at the very end of the recording , there was a terrible bastiaan noise .
and then he added , really quite emotional , which has ruined the whole experience .
but that didn 't have it .
what it was had ruined the memories of the experience .
he had had the experience .
he had had 20 minutes of music .
they were not because he was left with a memory . the memory was ruined , and the memory was everything he had gotten for keeping .
what this really tells us is that we could think about us and about other people in the sense of two types of the self .
there 's a erlebendes self that lives in the present and knows the present , is able to experience the past , but basically just the present .
it 's the self that anpricht cements the doctor  you know , if the doctor asks : " do it hurts now , if i anfasse here ? "
and then there 's an oldfashioned self , and the pollen self is the one that counts and receives the history of our lives , and it is the one that appeals to the doctor when he asks the question : " how did you feel lately ? "
or , " how was your trip to albania ? " or something like that .
these are two very different units , which cements self and the pollen self , and that is to confuse two part of the turmoil of the notion of happiness .
now , the pollen self is a storyteller .
and it really starts with a basic response to our memories of  it begins immediately .
not only do we tell stories , if we make us to tell stories .
our memory tells us stories , in other words , what we can retain from our experiences is a story .
and let me start with an example .
there 's an old study .
these are real patients who undergo a painful procedure .
i won 't go into detail . it is no longer painful , but it was painful , as this study was conducted in the 1990 s .
they were asked to report every 60 seconds about their pain .
